The main goal of this collaborative research project is to prepare the ground for the construction project of DarkSide-20k, a direct dark matter search whose ambition is to bring the sensitivity close to the so-called `neutrino fog', the sensitivity level where neutrinos start contributing a handful of background events in the form of nuclear coherent scatters.


Thanks to the collaborative research project for which this report is presently issued, the NSF-supported groups part of The Global Argon Dark


Matter Collaboration (GADMC) have advanced preparation of the DarkSide-20k design and project construction execution.


The DarkSide-20k detector is designed to search for dark matter by observing its scatters on target nuclei in 49.7t of liquid argon with essentially no un-tagged background from any known physics source beyond coherent neutrino scattering. Any remaining events in the detector then become a potential dark matter discovery. Several elements are essential for DarkSide-20k to achieve this goal. These are:


Use of an underground argon (UAr) target with Ar-39 reduced by a factor of 1,400 or higher with respect to atmospheric argon; Use of the scintillation light signal for energy measurement and pulse-shape discrimination (PSD) against backgrounds; Precise (mm-like) tri-dimensional event position reconstruction by exploiting the ionization signal;


Presence of an effective active neutron veto surrounding the LAr Time Projection Chamber (TPC);


Provision of excellent passive shielding from background radiation by a LAr bath also instrumented to act as an active muon veto. These techniques will be implemented by a combination of innovative yet proven and demonstrated technologies, including low-radioactivity argon from underground sources, SiPM-based cryogenic photosensors, a ProtoDUNE-like cryostat filled with atmospheric argon (AAr), and a LAr TPC constructed from low-background gadolinium-loaded polymethyl methacrylate (PMMA, commonly known as acrylic).


The DarkSide-20k experiment is expected to extend the cross-section versus mass range sensitivity in the search for dark matter to 4.610-48 cm2 for a 90 % C.L. exclusion and 1.510-47 cm2 at a 5 discovery significance for a 1TeV/c2 WIMP over a 200 tonne-year exposure, well beyond any current or presently funded experiment. This search will lead to the discovery, confirmation, or exclusion of the WIMP dark matter hypothesis down to the limit of the `neutrino fog'. DarkSide-20k will also be sensitive to a galactic supernova neutrino burst originating anywhere in the Milky Way Galaxy and to signals from solar neutrinos.


NSF-supported groups are involved in several key elements that are necessary for achieving this goal: extraction of low-radioactivity argon from underground sources with the Urania plant and the development of the DArT-in-ArDM facility to measure the 39Ar content of UAr and the Aria cryogenic distillation plant, development of a LAr TPC read out by SiPM-based cryogenic photosensors and housed in an acrylic vessel, development of cryogenic, purification and calibration systems, finalization of the DarkSide-20k detector design through the construction and operations of a smaller prototype detector, construction, integration, installation, and operations of the DarkSide-20k detector.


Collaborative grants PHY-1622415, PHY-1622327, PHY-1622345, PHY-162233, and collaborative grants PHY-1812540, PHY-1812472, PHY 1812471, PHY-1812504. PHY-1812492, PHY-1812547, PHY-1812482, PHY-1812453, and PHY-1812480 have the same scientific scope. The first group of grants (PHY-16XXXXX) is for special grants for the development of DarkSide-20k, while the second is for the base support of the US groups during the construction of the DarkSide-20k experiment. All grants have been awarded in the same year, month, and day, and some activities are shared among the two. For these reasons, some sections of the pertinent annual reports for all these grants are overlapped.
At UCLA, throughout the period of performance of the grant under consideration, we specifically focused on the following activities:








Commissioning, operation, and data analysis of the DarkSide-50 experiment;


Operation and maintenance of the DarkSide-50 experiment;


Development of DarkSide specific cryogenic system for handling the underground argon target.


Fabricated, assembled, tested the Darkide-20 cryogenics component at CERN in Geneva.


Delivered the UCLA responsible components to LNGS and completed the system design to the DarkSide collaboration.


Development and prototyping of the cryogenic components specifically designed for the DarkSide-20k experiment;


Engineering design and engineering reports for the DarkSide-20k experiment cryogenics and the detector TPC;


contributed to the development of the intensive care ventilator known as MVM "Milan Mechanical Ventilator" in response to the COVID-19 crisis;




